at is a User Story?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">19. How are user stories, epics, and tasks different?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">20. What is a Sprint?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">21. What is Velocity?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">22. What are the responsibilities of a Product Owner?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">23. What is a Burnup and Burndown Chart?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">24. How is Estimation Done in a Scrum Project?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>25. What are some risks in Scrum? How are they handled?<\/strong><\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">26. How does a Scrum Master track Sprint progress?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>27. How to deal with Score Creep?<\/strong><\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">28. What are MVP and MMP?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">29. What does DoD mean?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">30. How can a Scrum Master be a Servant Leader?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">31. How can you coordinate between multiple teams?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">32. What are the Scrum values?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">33. How would you handle conflict within the team?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">34. How would you deal with a difficult stakeholder?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">35. What are the three pillars of Scrum?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">36. Explain user story structure with an example.<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">37. How can you assure that the user stories meet the requirements?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">38. What are the five steps of Risk Management?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">39. What do you mean by timeboxing in Scrum? When can a Sprint be canceled, and by whom?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">40. What do you understand about Scope Creep? How can Scope Creep be managed?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">41. When should a Scrum Master not act as a facilitator?&nbsp;<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">42. How do you make different stakeholders attend daily scrum meetings?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">43. What is the structure of a good story?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">44. What is the role of a Scrum Master in a sprint retrospective?&nbsp;<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">45. How can Scrum Masters ensure timely delivery of action items?&nbsp;<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">46. What exactly do you mean by Sprint in Scrum?<br>47. What does the concept of Confidence Vote mean in Scrum? Why is it vital?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">48. Is a daily meeting suggested for all teams, irrespective of their size or experience level? Explain.<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">49. Can the Scrum team members participate in the product development process? If so, please explain how.<br>50. In Scrum, what do you mean by user stories? What benefits come from using them?<br><br>51. Why aren&#8217;t the user stories&#8217; man-hours estimated?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"> Scrum Master Interview Questions  And Answers<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>What is Scrum?<\/strong><br>Ans. Scrum is an agile framework for managing and developing projects. It provides a flexible, collaborative approach to software development that emphasizes iterative progress, adaptability, and customer satisfaction. Scrum organizes work into time-boxed iterations called sprints, typically lasting two to four weeks.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Define the roles in Scrum?<\/strong><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Product Owner:<\/strong> Represents the stakeholders, defines the product backlog, and ensures the team is working on the most valuable features.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Scrum Master:<\/strong> Facilitates the Scrum process, removes impediments, and ensures the team follows the Scrum principles.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Development Team:<\/strong> A cross-functional group responsible for delivering the product incrementally.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>3.<strong>What are the responsibilities of the Scrum Team?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<br>The Scrum Team collaboratively works on delivering a potentially releasable product increment each sprint. This includes planning, designing, developing, testing, and delivering the product.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>4.<strong>Differentiate Between Agile and Scrum.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Agile:<\/strong> A broad set of principles emphasizing adaptability, collaboration, and customer feedback in software development.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Scrum:<\/strong> A specific agile framework with defined roles, events, and artifacts for managing work in iterative cycles.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>5.<strong>What are the Artifacts of the Scrum Process?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Product Backlog:<\/strong> An ordered list of features and enhancements representing the work to be done.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Sprint Backlog:<\/strong> The subset of the product backlog selected for a sprint.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Increment:<\/strong> The sum of all the completed product backlog items in a sprint.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>6.<strong>How are the Product and Sprint Backlog different from One Another?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Product Backlog:<\/strong> Contains all features, enhancements, and fixes for a product.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Sprint Backlog:<\/strong> Contains the subset of items from the product backlog that the team commits to completing during a specific sprint.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>7.<strong>Who is a Scrum Master? And what does he\/she do?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Scrum Master:<\/strong> A facilitator and servant-leader for the Scrum Team.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Responsibilities:<\/strong> Removes impediments, coaches the team in Scrum principles, and ensures adherence to Scrum practices.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>8.<strong>What happens in Daily Stand-up sessions?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>A brief, daily meeting where the Scrum Team discusses progress, challenges, and plans for the day.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Each team member answers three questions: What did I do yesterday? What will I do today? Are there any impediments?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>9.<strong>What is Scrum-ban?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>A hybrid approach that combines Scrum and Kanban principles.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Allows for flexibility by incorporating elements of both frameworks.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>10.<strong>What is Sprint 0 and Spike?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Ans.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Sprint 0:<\/strong> An optional initial sprint for project setup, planning, and preparation.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Spike:<\/strong> A time-boxed investigation or research task undertaken to gather information or reduce uncertainty about a specific aspect of the project.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br><br><\/h3>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>1. What is Scrum? 2. Define the roles in Scrum? 3. What are the responsibilities of the Scrum Team? 4. Differentiate Between Agile and Scru